    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA242-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟi maṟuttarāniṉṟa talaimakaṉ kār kaṇṭu pākaṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE, who was bringing back [his] wealth after having accomplished [it], said to the charioteer upon seeing the season.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA242">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ilaiyil piṭava mīrmala rarumpap</l>
<l>            putalivar taḷavam pūṅkoṭi yaviḻap</l>
<l>            poṉṉeṉak koṉṟai malara maṇiyeṉap</l>
<l>            paṉmalark kāyāṅ kuṟuñciṉai kañalak</l>
<l>            kārtuṭaṅ kiṉṟē kālai valviraintu </l>
<l>            celka pākaniṉ ṟērē yuvakkāṇ</l>
<l>            kaḻippeyar kaḷariṟ pōkiya maṭamāṉ</l>
<l>            viḻikkaṭ pētaiyō ṭiṉaṉirin tōṭak</l>
<l>            kāmar neñcamō ṭakalāt</l>
<l>            tēṭūu niṉṟa viralai yēṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">While the wet blossoms of the leafless Piṭavam bud,</l>
<l rend="indent">while the flower creepers of the golden jasmine open, climbing the bushes,</l>
<l rend="indent">while the gold-like Laburnum blossoms,</l>
<l rend="indent4">while the short twigs</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the ironwood-tree are dense with many sapphire-like blossoms,</l>
<l>the rainy season has begun.</l>
<l rend="indent3">In great hurry this time<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kālai</term>, open-ended postposition, can be read as part of both sentences: either the time of the rainy season has come, or it is a time of hurry (or rather both).</note></l>
<l>let go, charioteer, your chariot. 	</l>
<l rend="indent3">See there:</l>
<l rend="indent">the Iralai stag that kept seeking,</l>
<l rend="indent">not parting with [its] desirous heart,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the group<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iṉam</term> is a bit uncomfortable here. From the context we would rather expect (and this is what T.V.G. reads) the usual triad of stag and doe with young one, but this is not usually called <term xml:lang="ta">iṉam</term>.</note> of youthful deer retreats [and] runs with the open-</l>
<l rend="indent2">eyed young ones<note place="foot">Here T.V.G. reads <term xml:lang="ta">pētaiyoṭu</term> as a metonymy for the young of the deer. As for position and context this is quite possible, but it makes also sense to take it in the usual way: the deer run "with open-eyed folly", that is, they are perturbed and simply fleeing.</note> from the saline soil where backwaters are moving.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
